00:25:14.439 --> 00:25:15.839
So there's actually a few things going on here.

00:25:15.920 --> 00:25:20.040
Um, I should, this is actually an important enough digression that

00:25:20.119 --> 00:25:21.000
I'm going to do it right now.

00:25:21.319 --> 00:25:28.079
Um, current guest letters is, it's a, it will return a list and you see that

00:25:28.599 --> 00:25:34.319
and you see that I'm copying this list, modifying it, and then setting a current

00:25:34.319 --> 00:25:38.479
guest letters to that new list instead of just taking that list and modifying it.

00:25:39.199 --> 00:25:44.439
So the reason for that is because this is a reactive value.

00:25:44.479 --> 00:25:50.119
And in order for it to sort of inform everyone that consumes, like all the

00:25:50.119 --> 00:25:55.640
things that use that reactive value, um, they need to, they need to know like,

00:25:55.640 --> 00:26:00.880
Hey, the value here has changed, uh, in order for them to invalidate and

00:26:00.920 --> 00:26:02.359
to know that they have to recompute.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:09.319
Now, if I just changed, if I were to just take this and then append Q to it and

00:26:09.319 --> 00:26:15.599
not do this copying and setting stuff, uh, then I would modify that list, but

00:26:15.599 --> 00:26:18.800
I wouldn't, I wouldn't be informing everyone that it had been updated.

00:26:19.199 --> 00:26:24.520
So, um, and also it could confuse some of the other, uh, some other code.

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:27.000
Like if I just modify that object in place.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:30.439
So that's actually one important difference between Python and R is that

00:26:30.439 --> 00:26:33.959
in R, most of these things, most objects are immutable.

00:26:34.479 --> 00:26:39.800
Um, and so you, you actually can't cause this sort of problem, but in Python,

00:26:40.119 --> 00:26:45.000
you have to be, you have to be sort of aware of, you know, what, what objects

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:48.560
can be changed in place and how that can, um, that can cause problems

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:50.160
with this reactive computation.

00:26:50.439 --> 00:26:54.000
Now, I don't think that, you know, Shiny is unique in this, in this respect.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.000
Like I know if you're working with like pandas data frames, the

00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:58.640
same thing can also happen.

00:26:59.119 --> 00:27:01.239
But it is one more thing to be aware of, uh, compared

00:27:01.239 --> 00:27:02.239
to the R version of Shiny.

00:27:02.439 --> 00:27:06.719
We would have to do this for like every single key on our keyboard.

00:27:06.880 --> 00:27:07.239
